Click on the figures for larger ones.

<h2>Event in April 2021</h2>
<br><br>
<br><br>
<strong>The very cold spells during the month across large parts of Europe</strong>
<br><br>
The month started with unusually mild conditions in many places, but temperatures dropped over an extensive region in the first week of the month, reaching record lows over parts of western and central Europe, for example over Slovenia. France was among the countries suffering substantial frost damage to vines and fruit trees that had begun developing earlier than usual. This led its government to declare a "calamit&#233; agricole".
<br><br>
Over several countries winds were more persistently from the north than is typical for April, with the United Kingdom experiencing its lowest average minimum temperature for April since 1922 and the highest number of April frosts in a data record going back to 1960.
<br><br>
The peak in this cold episode occured around 6-8 April. Many areas across the northern Balkans had seen even lower temperatures than they were during the last winter 2020/21. 2021 set a new record having temperatures lower in April than January. In Slovenia, the weather station Nova vas na Blokah hit -20.6 &deg;C and set the new official lowest temperature for April (the previous record at the station Nova vas was -18.0 &deg;C set on April 4th, 1970). Even if it would have happened in March, it would have been extremely rare. This is just a plain example of how extremely cold and historic this event and this morning was for April.
<br><br>
The main reason for these extreme cold records was the Arctic cold air mass that spread across a large part of Europe in the first week of April. Clear (no clouds) nights with barely any winds and fresh snow on the ground with dry air mass in the mid-levels are an ideal recipe for extreme cooling in the nighttime hours.
<br><br>
The main trigger for this cold April month was the clearly persistent blocked weather pattern with high pressure from Greenland towards the United Kingdom. On the eastern flank northerly winds in combination with clearings inland and wintry showers at the coasts were dominant over many areas of western and central Europe.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/apr2021/MSLP_anomaly_April_2021_Europe-final.png"><img alt="" src="../images/apr2021/MSLP_anomaly_April_2021_Europe-final.png" width="300px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Mean sea level pressure anomaly April 2021 (source: Climate Explorer KNMI)</em>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/apr2021/Analyses_Europe_6_April_2021_12_UTC.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/apr2021/Analyses_Europe_6_April_2021_12_UTC.jpg" width="300px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Weather analysis Europe 6 April 2021 12 UTC (source: KNMI)</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for April 2021</h2>
<br><br>
The cold April 2021 was particularly characterized by its outstandingly high number of frost days in much of Europe (Figure 3). Just to give a few numbers: The United Kingdom recorded an average of 14 frost days that month, compared to a long-term average of 5 days in the period 1981-2010. Similarly in Germany, the number of frost days was almost 13 on country average, the highest number since 1929, compared to 5 on long-term average 1981-2010. Much of Scandinavia had frost during the whole month, even there the number was higher than normal. Also some southern parts of Europe (southern France, northern Italy, the Balkans) noted more frost days than usual.
It is important to mention that these are the numbers of air frost, while the number of ground frost days was even much higher, e.g. 22 ground frost days in the United Kingdom (12 on long-term average).
However, there were also areas in Europe, which were less frosty than usual. Over European Russia, warm subtropical air reached even its northernmost parts.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/apr2021/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_fd_2021_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_fdETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2021-04-15T12-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/apr2021/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_fd_2021_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_fdETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2021-04-15T12-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/apr2021/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_fd_anom_2021_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_fdETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2021-04-15T12-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/apr2021/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_fd_anom_2021_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_fdETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2021-04-15T12-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3: FD: Number of frost days in April 2021 (left) and anomaly w.r.t. 1981-2010 (right) (E-OBS)</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Interesting was also the distribution of wet days (days with at least 1 mm of precipitation) in Europe (Figure 4). Much of Western, Central and Northern Europe counted less than 10 wet days, so it was almost dry most of the month. In some places of France and the United Kingdom, there were even no wet days at all - very untypical for an April in Western Europe.
In contrast, eastern parts of Europe recorded more wet days than normal. The reason is again the distribution of pressure centres in Europe as shown in Figure 1: Very high pressure on monthly average over Northwestern Europe and much lower pressure further east.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/apr2021/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r1mm_2021_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_r1mmETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2021-04-15T12-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/apr2021/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r1mm_2021_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_r1mmETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2021-04-15T12-00-00Z.png" ></a>
